ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the potentiality of the prepared materials as photocatalysts, the catalytic performance of the GQD/AgVO3 heterojunctions with different GQD contents were examined for the photodegradation of IBP under visible light illumination followed by HPLC monitoring. The photocatalytic activities in Fig. 5
                        a clearly indicate that GQD/AgVO3 heterojunctions exhibit higher activity than pure rutile AgVO3 nanoribbons. For GQD/AgVO3 heterojunctions, the photocatalytic activity first increases with increasing GQD content, reaches a maximal at the GQD content of 3wt% and then begins to decrease. The photodegradation rate of IBP with 3wt%-GQD/AgVO3 composite is more than 90% within 120min under visible light irradiation, while other photocatalysts show relatively low degradation efficiencies under the same conditions, suggesting 3wt%-GQD/AgVO3 composite exhibits a high visible-light photocatalytic degradation capacity. Meanwhile, the photocatalytic properties of 3wt%-GQD/AgVO3 composite were better than the similarly loaded GS/AgVO3 composite (Fig. S9a). There was almost no degradation effect with the later one, since larger GSs attaching on the surface of AgVO3 hindering the visible-light absorption of AgVO3. The UV–vis absorption spectra of GS/AgVO3 composite were illustrated in Fig. S9b. The photocatalytic reduction of IBP over 3wt%-GQD/AgVO3 heterojunctions was determined by HPLC. The starting solution of IBP exhibits one main absorption bands located at 4.4min, which are related to the benzene ring (Fig. S10). After irradiation, the intensity of these bands decreases markedly due to fast photocatalytic oxidation of IBP. Interestingly, this is accompanied by the appearance of the new band near 6.2min. This strongly indicates the formation of reaction intermediates. This band starts to arise immediately in the first period of photocatalytic treatment (after 30min), and reaches maximum after 90min of photocatalytic treatment. More than 95% of this intermediate is degraded after 180min indicating incomplete degradation. However, with a further increasing of the GQD content more than 3wt%, the photocatalytic degradation efficiency declined. This phenomenon is probably due to the opacity and light scattering of the excess GQDs decreasing the absorption of incident light, and reducing catalytic active sites [39]. As depicted in Fig. 5b, the apparent rate constants calculated from the degradation curves of −ln(C/C0
                        ) vs. irradiation time are 0.0015, 0.0034, 0.0077, 0.022, 0.0065 and 0.0043min−1 for 0, 0.5, 1, 3, 5, and 7wt% of GQD contents in composite, respectively. The photocatalytic efficiency of 3wt%-GQD/AgVO3 composite is about 5 times that of pure AgVO3 nanoribbons.
